= El Palacio Negro

MÉXICO, D.F., noviembre de 1968 —

Lecumberri was built in 1900 as a model prison, a Porfirian panopticon of radiating corridors called *crujías*. The politicals are kept in Crujía M, and by now it is the best political education in the country: Demetrio Vallejo, nine years inside, still writing union circulars nobody may deliver; Valentín Campa, who has spent more of his life in prison than in the party he helped build; and since September and October, the new class — CNH delegates, brigade kids of nineteen, professors picked up at their blackboards, the engineer Heberto Castillo taken half-dead from a beating, the philosopher Eli de Gortari, and José Revueltas.

Revueltas, the country's greatest living novelist of prisons, has solved the government's evidentiary problem by writing a letter claiming *intellectual authorship* of the entire student movement — a confession constructed as an indictment, since a state that accepts it admits it is jailing an idea. They put him in Crujía M with the rest. He seems almost at home, which is the saddest thing anyone has seen there.

Outside, the families have organized themselves with the terrible efficiency of grief: Sunday queues with baskets, lists of names, a rotation of lawyers filing *amparos* that the judges deny like men swatting flies. Word has come, too, from the common crujías: the authorities are letting it be known that on some convenient day the apolitical prisoners will be sent into M with clubs, and the guards will be busy elsewhere. The families are asking, plainly: is the Party with us or not?

- @defensa: Fund the legal defense committees. Lawyers, visits, names published abroad — make each prisoner too famous to disappear.
- @clandestino: Conserve everything. Rebuild the cells first; the prisoners, of all people, would understand.

