The cells are rebuilt, quietly, five by five — no member knowing more than four others, the old discipline from the forties, correct by every manual ever written in exile. The Party will survive, and survival is not nothing; ask anyone who has watched a party die.

But in the visiting yard at Lecumberri on Sunday, a mother from the Politécnico — her son is nineteen, his crime was a mimeograph — asks your comrade's wife what the Party is doing for the boys inside. And there is an answer, a correct answer about the long term and the relationship of forces, and nobody can say it to her face.
